## Assessing the Documentation Needs of Human Rights Defenders
### Looking Back on OpenArchive’s DAC Cohort One
By Natalie Cadranel, Lauren Salim, and Claire August

</ArticleHeaderSection>
<ContentSection>

At OpenArchive, we work to create a more just, equitable, and sustainable media ecosystem where people's history is the primary history. 

We do this by 
1. partnering with Decentralized Archivist Communities (DACs) to jointly support decentralization, archiving, and preservation efforts to ensure human rights documentation is safe and accessible in the long term; 

2. building responsive tools like our **_Save_** app which helps eyewitnesses preserve, protect, authenticate and amplify crucial records of human rights abuses; 

3. developing best practice guides on preserving evidence and combatting disinformation; and 4) conducting co-research with at-risk communities around the world. 

Our [DAC Program](https://open-archive.org/programs) is one of the key ways we interact with communities that are documenting and preserving evidentiary media. Working with a community manager with deep regional knowledge, we provide needs assessments, security and archival workshops, assistance with internal documentation and workflows, *****_Save_***** implementation and integration with organizations’ backend archives, and funding to support their activities and archives.

Through the collaboration, we gain valuable insights into the needs, frustrations, workflows, limitations, and threats our user communities face. This research allows us to adapt and update the *****_Save_***** app and customize workshops, trainings, and guides. We publish our research findings to share with the broader community of archival and human rights practitioners and scholars.

Most importantly, the communities we work with can grow or strengthen their archiving and documentation processes.


##### A Look at Cohort 1


OpenArchive is fortunate to collaborate with inspiring Decentralized Archivist Communities (DACs) who are actively defending human rights worldwide. In 2023, we had seven DACs from [Eastern Europe](https://open-archive.org/programs/our-users/eastern-europe), [MENA](https://open-archive.org/programs/our-users/mena), the [United States of America](https://open-archive.org/programs/our-users/north-america), and [Latin America](https://open-archive.org/programs/our-users/latam) who work to document violations 

and safeguard evidence despite escalating challenges and human rights abuses.

